After their period of growth, in preparation of their return trip to the spawning grounds, the eels transform into silver eel. Once the eel has undergone pre-puberty or “silvering”, which is accompanied by marked changes in morphology, body constitution and other features (see Chapter 2), it is ready to start its spawning migration. Its lifestyle changes radically. As we have seen in Chapter 2, silver eels stop feeding, they have already acquired salinity tolerance while still living in freshwater and finally they have begun their puberty. As European eels, Anguilla anguilla, spawn in the Sarga\sso sea, the silver eels must migrate from inland or coastal waters over a distance of about 6,000 km to reach this area. Somehow silver eels are triggered by environmental factors to start their migration.},
